INSERT OR IGNORE INTO books (title, word_count, preview, full_text) VALUES
('Alice in Wonderland', 500, 'Alice was beginning to get very tired of sitting...', 'Alice was beginning to get very tired of sitting by her sister on the bank, and of having nothing to do: once or twice she had peeped into the book her sister was reading, but it had no pictures or conversations in it, "and what is the use of a book," thought Alice "without pictures or conversation?"'),
('Sherlock Holmes', 800, 'To Sherlock Holmes she is always the woman...', 'To Sherlock Holmes she is always the woman. I have seldom heard him mention her under any other name. In his eyes she eclipses and predominates the whole of her sex. It was not that he felt any emotion akin to love for Irene Adler.');
('The World of Bees', 604, 'Bees are remarkable winged insects belonging to the clade Anthophila within the order Hymenoptera. With more than 20,000 known species, they represent one of the most diverse and ecologically significant groups of insects on Earth. While a few species live in organized colonies, most bees are solitary creatures.', 'The World of Bees\n\nBees are remarkable winged insects belonging to the clade Anthophila within the order Hymenoptera. With more than 20,000 known species, they represent one of the most diverse and ecologically significant groups of insects on Earth. While a few species, such as honey bees, bumblebees, and stingless bees, live in highly organized colonies, the overwhelming majority of bees lead solitary lives, independently building nests and raising their offspring.\n\nUnlike their close relatives, wasps and ants, bees are herbivores that feed primarily on nectar and pollen from flowering plants. Nectar provides carbohydrates for energy, whereas pollen supplies the proteins and nutrients required for larval development. Bees inhabit nearly every region of the world except Antarctica.\n\nFrom an ecological perspective, bees are indispensable pollinators. As they move from flower to flower, they transfer pollen between plants, enabling fertilization and the production of seeds and fruits. A large portion of the global food supply depends on this process.\n\nThe evolutionary history of bees stretches back more than 120 million years to the Early Cretaceous period. Scientists believe bees evolved from predatory wasps whose diets gradually shifted toward pollen and nectar.\n\nCommunication and navigation in bees are sophisticated. Honey bees perform the waggle dance to communicate the direction and distance of food sources, using the sun and spatial memory to navigate landscapes.\n\nDespite their importance, bee populations face threats from pesticides, habitat loss, climate change, parasites, and disease. These pressures raise global concerns about pollinator decline and food security.\n\nHumans have practiced beekeeping for thousands of years, harvesting honey and managing colonies for pollination. Beyond agriculture, bees have long symbolized diligence, cooperation, and the intricate harmony of nature.');```
